# Managing Global Theming and Prop Forwarding in Large Design Systems

Great question! This is one of the core architectural challenges when scaling component libraries. Here's how major design systems tackle these problems:

## Global Theming Strategies

**Context-Based Theming** is the most common approach:
```jsx
// Theme provider at app root
<ThemeProvider theme={lightTheme}>
  <App />
</ThemeProvider>

// Components consume theme anywhere in tree
const Button = () => {
  const theme = useTheme();
  return <button style={{ color: theme.colors.primary }} />;
};
```

**CSS Custom Properties** for runtime theme switching:
```jsx
// Theme provider sets CSS variables
const ThemeProvider = ({ theme, children }) => {
  useEffect(() => {
    Object.entries(theme).forEach(([key, value]) => {
      document.documentElement.style.setProperty(`--${key}`, value);
    });
  }, [theme]);

  return children;
};
```

## Prop Forwarding Patterns

**Compound Components** reduce prop drilling:
```jsx
<Card>
  <Card.Header variant="highlighted" />
  <Card.Body padding="large" />
</Card>
```

**Render Props** for flexible composition:
```jsx
<DataProvider>
  {({ data, loading }) => (
    <Table data={data} loading={loading} />
  )}
</DataProvider>
```

**Polymorphic Components** with proper TypeScript support:
```jsx
interface ButtonProps<T extends ElementType = 'button'> {
  as?: T;
  variant?: 'primary' | 'secondary';
}

